<paragraph blockId="19.[111,647,1071,1352]" pageId="19" pageNumber="62">
In contrast, this leaf found associated with the previous one, shows a very thick (up to 
<quantity box="[495,559,1103,1130]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
) lamina and a superficial surface smooth. Sclerotic strands do not extend to the bundle sheath and intermediate strands occur between veins as illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="RENAULT B." box="[113,280,1230,1257]" pageId="19" pageNumber="62" pagination="213 - 348" refId="ref13831" refString="RENAULT B. 1879. - Structure comparee de quelques tiges de la flore Carbonifere, Nouvelles Archives du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle 2: 213 - 348." type="journal article" year="1879">Renault (1879)</bibRefCitation>
for specimens from Grand-Croix and by 
<bibRefCitation author="HARMS V. L. &amp; LEISMAN G. A." box="[193,475,1261,1288]" pageId="19" pageNumber="62" pagination="1041 - 1064" refId="ref13118" refString="HARMS V. L. &amp; LEISMAN G. A. 1961. - The anatomy and morphology of certain Cordaites leaves. Journal of Paleontology 35: 1041 - 1064." type="journal article" year="1961">Harms &amp; Leisman (1961)</bibRefCitation>
from American Pennsylvanian coal balls. The interval between veins is about 
<quantity box="[203,292,1325,1352]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
, i.e. about 14 veins per cm.
</paragraph>
